30
00:02:24,206 --> 00:02:26,047
So my first story is about this lady.

31
00:02:27,208 --> 00:02:31,271
She is the CEO of Congregate, where I work.

32
00:02:33,052 --> 00:02:36,135
More to the point, for this story, she's an aunt and she's a knitter.

33
00:02:39,237 --> 00:02:41,979
Emily's niece, Molly, is now seven.

34
00:02:42,259 --> 00:02:44,140
The picture's a little old, but it's such a cute picture.

35
00:02:45,661 --> 00:02:49,044
Molly asked Emily to make her a skirt, a knitted skirt.

36
00:02:49,947 --> 00:02:53,508
And those of you who have done any knitting know that this didn't happen overnight.

37
00:02:54,188 --> 00:02:56,249
But eventually, sure enough, there was a knitted skirt.

38
00:02:57,469 --> 00:03:00,070
But the problem was that it was a little big.

39
00:03:00,450 --> 00:03:01,430
It didn't quite fit.

40
00:03:02,371 --> 00:03:06,972
Molly slimmed through the hips, as many very young children are, and it just wasn't quite

41
00:03:06,992 --> 00:03:07,432
staying up.

42
00:03:08,573 --> 00:03:09,753
So Emily had a problem.

43
00:03:11,254 --> 00:03:12,394
And she didn't have a blueprint.

44
00:03:12,414 --> 00:03:13,294
She didn't have a pattern.

45
00:03:14,055 --> 00:03:19,396
What she did have was a crochet hook, an idea, and a willingness to try possible solutions.

46
00:03:20,654 --> 00:03:28,239
So she figured out how to knit belt loops, and she added a black ribbon belt to the skirt.

47
00:03:30,300 --> 00:03:34,543
And so the net result was that this skirt is dramatically cuter than it would have been

48
00:03:34,583 --> 00:03:35,244
without the belt.

49
00:03:35,444 --> 00:03:39,126
As soon as I saw this picture on Facebook, I went, oh, my God, that's it.

50
00:03:39,867 --> 00:03:43,829
That's the beautiful thing that can come out of a crisis.

51
00:03:45,852 --> 00:03:52,617
So what I'm hoping to tell you all about is ways in which you can find your communities

52
00:03:52,677 --> 00:03:56,781
are in crisis, things are going wrong, and you're not going to know what to do.

53
00:03:57,101 --> 00:04:03,246
But figure out what you can do, think creatively, move forward, and hopefully you're going to

54
00:04:03,326 --> 00:04:07,209
end up with something that's better than it would have been if you had never had the crisis

55
00:04:07,350 --> 00:04:07,630
at all.

56
00:04:10,252 --> 00:04:11,753
So a little bit about Congregate.

57
00:04:13,855 --> 00:04:14,536
Eric, where are you?

58
00:04:16,631 --> 00:04:19,612
I chose this screenshot before I knew Eric was going to be here.

59
00:04:19,652 --> 00:04:21,593
That's his game, Crusaders of the Lost Isles.

60
00:04:22,613 --> 00:04:25,694
But anyway, we have over 100,000 games.

61
00:04:25,774 --> 00:04:27,134
It's a gaming platform.

62
00:04:28,155 --> 00:04:31,236
Any developer can upload their game to our site.

63
00:04:32,316 --> 00:04:38,738
They get, in exchange for that, they can have player feedback, and they get a portion of

64
00:04:38,778 --> 00:04:41,319
the advertising revenue that's earned by their game page.

65
00:04:42,725 --> 00:04:49,490
If they have purchases in their game, they can integrate our virtual goods API and earn

66
00:04:49,510 --> 00:04:50,491
some additional money that way.

67
00:04:51,211 --> 00:04:55,414
We usually have about 300 to 400 virtual goods games on the site at any one time.

68
00:04:55,434 --> 00:04:59,657
A couple hundred forums, lots of different kinds of chat rooms.

69
00:05:00,218 --> 00:05:00,958
There's a lot going on.

70
00:05:04,118 --> 00:05:10,099
Within a month or so of my becoming community manager, Kongregate had one of the biggest

71
00:05:10,419 --> 00:05:12,060
community crises in our history.

72
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:13,900
So that was great timing.

73
00:05:15,361 --> 00:05:19,902
In the process of trying to manage that crisis, we made a lot of mistakes.

74
00:05:21,502 --> 00:05:25,203
Quite a few of those mistakes made things a lot worse instead of better.

75
00:05:26,623 --> 00:05:31,285
And so when we did our postmortem at the end of about two weeks, here was how it started.

76
00:05:37,015 --> 00:05:38,637
And the lady who wrote that is sitting here too.

77
00:05:42,163 --> 00:05:45,425
But the point is that not everything we did made things worse.

78
00:05:45,806 --> 00:05:49,769
And so we paid attention to what made things worse and we talked with each other and we

79
00:05:49,809 --> 00:05:52,491
kept doing more of the things that didn't make it worse.

80
00:05:53,251 --> 00:05:58,335
And so it was expensive and it took a lot of time, it took a lot of work over those

81
00:05:58,375 --> 00:06:04,420
couple weeks, but by the end of it we had actually figured out the basis of how we handle

82
00:06:04,780 --> 00:06:07,162
all our community crises from now on.

83
00:06:07,342 --> 00:06:07,882
Ever since then.

84
00:06:08,763 --> 00:06:11,985
The things that we learned in that crisis have been what we do.

85
00:06:13,946 --> 00:06:18,989
And we also made a lot of really great relationships with players, and a lot of those folks are

86
00:06:19,009 --> 00:06:20,190
still playing on our site.

87
00:06:21,451 --> 00:06:24,573
I get messages from them sometimes, hey, can you take a look at this game?

88
00:06:24,653 --> 00:06:25,694
It's giving me some trouble.

89
00:06:25,754 --> 00:06:28,175
I really appreciate that thing you did four years ago.

90
00:06:28,195 --> 00:06:29,956
I'm like, sure, I'll take a look.

91
00:06:30,136 --> 00:06:30,557
That's great.

92
00:06:32,618 --> 00:06:37,201
So I never would have thought it at the time, but in retrospect, I do believe that.

93
00:06:38,483 --> 00:06:41,804
The effort and the financial costs were entirely worthwhile.

94
00:06:43,105 --> 00:06:44,365
We absolutely got...

95
00:06:44,385 --> 00:06:49,288
It was worth the cost, is what I'm saying.

96
00:06:50,348 --> 00:06:54,490
And since then, I have had front row seats as many different developers have had many

97
00:06:54,510 --> 00:06:56,591
different kinds of crises with their communities.

98
00:06:58,704 --> 00:07:04,966
On a day-to-day basis on Kongregate, the developers and their community managers handle the crises

99
00:07:04,986 --> 00:07:05,486
that come up.

100
00:07:06,267 --> 00:07:10,728
But for something to escalate up to the point where it comes to my attention usually means

101
00:07:10,788 --> 00:07:14,290
that everything is really hitting the fan and nobody has any idea what to do.

102
00:07:15,990 --> 00:07:21,613
But the thing is that all community crises fundamentally come down to one issue, and

103
00:07:21,653 --> 00:07:22,673
that's loss of trust.

104
00:07:25,639 --> 00:07:28,304
For some reason, in some way, players are disappointed.

105
00:07:28,324 --> 00:07:36,217
I had a lot of fun Googling disappointed cute animals for this slide.

106
00:07:38,756 --> 00:07:40,397
Something did not go as expected.

107
00:07:40,737 --> 00:07:42,878
They could be there was a bug in the game.

108
00:07:43,119 --> 00:07:46,201
It could be that you didn't meet a launch date.

109
00:07:47,001 --> 00:07:50,884
Maybe it was that they went looking for some support and couldn't find any.

110
00:07:51,484 --> 00:07:53,926
It could also be that they had unrealistic expectations.

111
00:07:54,066 --> 00:07:58,529
But for whatever reason, they don't trust you to make things right.

112
00:07:59,550 --> 00:08:04,833
So to resolve your crisis, you need to rebuild trust and a confidence in you and how you're

113
00:08:04,973 --> 00:08:06,474
going to handle problems in the future.

114
00:08:07,255 --> 00:08:08,176
And this is possible.

115
00:08:09,837 --> 00:08:15,621
And more to the point, it's also possible that after you've done that, your community

116
00:08:15,661 --> 00:08:19,104
will know you better, they'll trust you more, and you'll have a better rapport than you

117
00:08:19,124 --> 00:08:20,345
would have otherwise.

118
00:08:22,687 --> 00:08:29,992
So there is exactly one tool that all of us bring to every situation that we're in, and

119
00:08:30,032 --> 00:08:30,593
it's ourselves.

120
00:08:31,513 --> 00:08:33,215
In social work, this is called use of self.

121
00:08:33,315 --> 00:08:34,296
The understanding that...

122
00:08:35,721 --> 00:08:42,108
The persona that we present will have an effect on whatever situation we find ourselves

123
00:08:42,168 --> 00:08:42,268
in.

124
00:08:43,269 --> 00:08:46,332
And so this means that you're a tool.

125
00:08:48,174 --> 00:08:49,796
And I have pretty much the best job ever.

126
00:08:51,718 --> 00:08:54,060
No, but persona, you are a tool.

127
00:08:54,581 --> 00:08:58,264
And how people see you is what determines how they respond to you.

128
00:08:59,377 --> 00:09:03,738
You'll be most effective in both preventing and managing crises if you're able to convey

129
00:09:03,779 --> 00:09:06,360
that you are intelligent, principled, and fair.

130
00:09:07,300 --> 00:09:12,862
When I'm interacting with frustrated players, I'm sympathetic, but I'm also competent and

131
00:09:12,922 --> 00:09:13,443
in charge.

132
00:09:15,103 --> 00:09:19,025
My underlying message is I care about your happiness and I am here to fix this.

133
00:09:22,417 --> 00:09:26,700
Competent, principled, and fair is not at all the same thing as I know exactly what

134
00:09:26,740 --> 00:09:28,842
we are going to do and we'll have this done by EOD.

135
00:09:31,284 --> 00:09:33,425
Sometimes you'll know from the beginning what you're going to do.

136
00:09:34,266 --> 00:09:38,049
Other times you're going to sort of have to dive in there with your metaphorical crochet

137
00:09:38,089 --> 00:09:40,371
hook and figure out how to make some bell loops.

138
00:09:41,732 --> 00:09:47,216
But the most important tool you'll have at your disposal is not a crochet hook, but yourself.

139
00:09:49,012 --> 00:09:51,674
Like any tool, you need to know what you can and cannot do.

140
00:09:52,434 --> 00:09:54,435
This Swiss Army knife has a lot of great features.

141
00:09:55,176 --> 00:09:58,017
But if you wanted to fry an egg, you're going to be sorely disappointed.

142
00:09:59,018 --> 00:10:02,720
Although I have spent some time thinking about how I would make a frying pan using those

143
00:10:02,780 --> 00:10:04,161
tools, but that's beside the point.

144
00:10:05,541 --> 00:10:10,924
Similarly, you need to be able to accurately assess what you can and cannot bring to community

145
00:10:10,944 --> 00:10:11,365
crises.

146
00:10:12,265 --> 00:10:16,768
Don't try to project a strength you don't have or it will damage your credibility because

147
00:10:16,808 --> 00:10:17,728
they're going to see through you.

148
00:10:19,027 --> 00:10:21,748
I am not the most tech savvy person who works at Congregate.

149
00:10:21,808 --> 00:10:25,230
In fact, I might be the least tech savvy person who works at Congregate.

150
00:10:25,290 --> 00:10:30,952
So when I dive into a crisis, there's a lot of, okay, so tell me what that means.

151
00:10:32,612 --> 00:10:38,454
But because I don't pretend to be anything other than who I am, players find that disarming

152
00:10:38,654 --> 00:10:40,975
instead of accusation worthy.

153
00:10:42,956 --> 00:10:47,159
So, owning who you are is going to be a great strength to you in the long run.

154
00:10:47,920 --> 00:10:51,543
Sometimes not easy, but it really is worth that journey.

155
00:10:54,525 --> 00:10:59,829
Now, jumping back to the first story, when I was talking about the skirt that Emily made,

156
00:10:59,849 --> 00:11:05,594
I feel the need to point out that she already knew how to knit when she started that skirt,

157
00:11:05,634 --> 00:11:06,034
didn't she?

158
00:11:06,174 --> 00:11:10,117
She had the core competencies that she needed to finish that project.

159
00:11:11,495 --> 00:11:16,641
And I'm sorry to say that not every community manager I meet is great at interacting with

160
00:11:16,701 --> 00:11:17,061
players.

161
00:11:17,341 --> 00:11:22,627
I'm sure that you all are amazing, but for the sake of thoroughness, I feel like I just

162
00:11:22,647 --> 00:11:24,689
need to touch on a couple of basics.

163
00:11:28,021 --> 00:11:32,443
One of the things that Congregate does is that we choose and train members of our community

164
00:11:32,503 --> 00:11:34,124
to be volunteer chat moderators.

165
00:11:35,284 --> 00:11:40,446
And when we train those people, we don't start out by telling them how the banning and silencing

166
00:11:40,486 --> 00:11:40,987
tools work.

167
00:11:41,427 --> 00:11:42,767
We don't start with punishment at all.

168
00:11:43,768 --> 00:11:49,170
What we do is we start with teaching them the tools that they need to manage the community,

169
00:11:49,390 --> 00:11:55,173
the chat room, and particular conversations without needing to resort to punitive measures.

170
00:11:56,694 --> 00:11:58,675
And I believe that community management is the same way.

171
00:11:59,276 --> 00:12:04,279
That if you develop a certain kind of relationship with people, they are going to be more likely

172
00:12:04,379 --> 00:12:08,803
to go in the direction that you are trying to herd them even though they are fundamentally

173
00:12:08,863 --> 00:12:10,804
cats.

174
00:12:10,824 --> 00:12:13,286
So here is the big secret.

175
00:12:14,207 --> 00:12:18,310
If people like and respect you, they will trust you and they will do what you want.

176
00:12:19,861 --> 00:12:25,664
It seems really obvious, doesn't it? And yet it's very common for people to overlook

177
00:12:25,684 --> 00:12:31,587
that, I would say. So this may come as a surprise, but Internet

178
00:12:31,628 --> 00:12:36,890
folks are not a big fan of authority figures. We are.

179
00:12:43,061 --> 00:12:48,785
We all go through a life phase called individuation, typically when we're adolescents, but not

180
00:12:48,845 --> 00:12:52,788
always, where we separate from our parents.

181
00:12:52,848 --> 00:12:56,311
We start to question the things that they're telling us.

182
00:12:57,051 --> 00:13:00,474
And we begin to challenge why they have authority at all.

183
00:13:00,794 --> 00:13:01,014
Right?

184
00:13:01,074 --> 00:13:04,617
Like, why do I have to listen to you?

185
00:13:04,697 --> 00:13:05,918
Let's explore that.

186
00:13:08,019 --> 00:13:11,782
I think a lot of players sort of present as though they are stuck in that phase.

187
00:13:12,663 --> 00:13:15,905
Some of them actually are still adolescents, and so that's life appropriate.

188
00:13:16,505 --> 00:13:21,549
But regardless, I think there's a culture on the Internet that says respect needs to

189
00:13:21,589 --> 00:13:21,969
be earned.

190
00:13:22,209 --> 00:13:23,810
It's not just granted to you automatically.

191
00:13:25,331 --> 00:13:30,495
So in the face of this skepticism, how are you going to go about earning respect and

192
00:13:30,535 --> 00:13:30,855
trust?

193
00:13:32,476 --> 00:13:35,618
So the first thing is to be lenient.

194
00:13:36,679 --> 00:13:40,782
If you address only the most important things, people are more likely to listen.

195
00:13:41,688 --> 00:13:45,749
Say you have two problems. On this hand you have people who are posting in your forum

196
00:13:45,870 --> 00:13:51,132
in text speak and it's annoying some of your players. Over here you have people who are

197
00:13:51,172 --> 00:13:55,913
telling other people to kill themselves. Now I hope that you're going to recognize that

198
00:13:55,933 --> 00:14:00,835
this is a much more important problem. And so if you don't yammer about this, but focus

199
00:14:00,895 --> 00:14:05,277
on this, people are going to pay attention, right? And so you want to appear reasonable

200
00:14:05,337 --> 00:14:08,418
to most people and you want to focus on the things that actually matter.

201
00:14:13,339 --> 00:14:18,406
I'm seeing a couple of people laugh. I love this slide. When I was redoing our moderator

202
00:14:18,446 --> 00:14:25,014
training a few years back, I Googled images fairness, and this is what I got. Be fair

203
00:14:25,294 --> 00:14:29,199
like the fairness frog, because the fairness frog is totally a thing. We've all heard of

204
00:14:29,219 --> 00:14:30,161
the fairness frog.

205
00:14:31,885 --> 00:14:33,765
And the randomness of that really appealed to me.

206
00:14:34,125 --> 00:14:37,567
In fact, some of our moderators got together and bought me a frog squishable and sent it

207
00:14:37,587 --> 00:14:42,588
to me.

208
00:14:42,608 --> 00:14:44,149
So be fair, like the fairness frog.

209
00:14:44,209 --> 00:14:51,191
But seriously, players will detect if you're biased, if you tend to be more lenient with

210
00:14:51,231 --> 00:14:52,411
people who are your friends.

211
00:14:53,183 --> 00:14:59,170
If you tend to be harsher to people who just annoy the piss out of you, they'll notice

212
00:14:59,491 --> 00:15:05,398
and they will go, mm, mm-hmm, this person is not really all that, because they're biased.

213
00:15:06,425 --> 00:15:09,126
The other thing that goes along with that is that you need to always be thinking about

214
00:15:09,146 --> 00:15:11,347
what's best for the community as a whole.

215
00:15:11,627 --> 00:15:13,008
You can't please every individual.

216
00:15:13,448 --> 00:15:19,711
Somebody's going to be pissed, but reasonable people will be able to look at your decisions

217
00:15:19,751 --> 00:15:25,234
and go, okay, so and so is annoyed, but she's clearly thinking about what's best for everybody.

218
00:15:26,034 --> 00:15:26,975
I'm going to give her a pass.

219
00:15:29,916 --> 00:15:33,358
So be lenient, or sorry, be nice, rather, but not a pushover.

220
00:15:34,398 --> 00:15:35,659
So if you're nice to people.

221
00:15:38,479 --> 00:15:41,021
They will be more likely to be nice to you.

222
00:15:41,421 --> 00:15:47,246
And also, if you are nice and calm, it makes it pretty much impossible to troll you.

223
00:15:47,886 --> 00:15:49,688
I could tell you stories, but then I'd run over.

224
00:15:52,290 --> 00:15:57,494
The other thing to keep in mind is that people will live up or down to your expectations.

225
00:15:58,075 --> 00:16:02,000
This sounds like something that is just sort of happy-clappy community manager nonsense,

226
00:16:02,020 --> 00:16:03,121
but it's like a real thing.

227
00:16:03,201 --> 00:16:08,027
Like, there's psychological research about how people subtly communicate expectations

228
00:16:08,067 --> 00:16:10,190
to each other and how people will...

229
00:16:12,853 --> 00:16:16,916
tried either to elevate themselves or debase themselves to meet those expectations.

230
00:16:16,956 --> 00:16:21,699
So if you treat people like they're punk kids, they'll probably act like punk kids.

231
00:16:22,239 --> 00:16:27,202
But if you treat them like they're human beings who are capable of coolness, they'll try.

232
00:16:27,483 --> 00:16:30,605
Like even if they are punk kids and they don't really know what that looks like, they're

233
00:16:30,625 --> 00:16:31,165
going to try.

234
00:16:34,399 --> 00:16:37,261
So, the last thing is to be transparent.

235
00:16:38,302 --> 00:16:43,006
As an authority figure, players are going to want to know what the limits of your authority

236
00:16:43,126 --> 00:16:44,247
are and how you use it.

237
00:16:44,927 --> 00:16:51,352
And if you're willing to talk to them, frankly, about what you do and why, they'll know that

238
00:16:51,472 --> 00:16:56,596
you are operating within the bounds of, if not law, then a structure, right?

239
00:16:56,676 --> 00:17:00,099
They're not going to get banned from the game just because you had a fight with your significant

240
00:17:00,159 --> 00:17:02,841
other or because it's raining and you hate the rain.

241
00:17:04,190 --> 00:17:09,994
That they're not subject to whims, that there's a structure for the authority and that's going

242
00:17:10,014 --> 00:17:11,115
to be reassuring to them.

243
00:17:12,716 --> 00:17:15,018
So finally, remember the silent majority.

244
00:17:15,298 --> 00:17:22,023
If you seem fair and reasonable, people will believe in you for the most part, even though

245
00:17:22,063 --> 00:17:23,424
some noisy complainers might not.

246
00:17:25,466 --> 00:17:28,888
So having covered the basics, let's talk a little bit about how to

247
00:17:30,783 --> 00:17:35,044
Manage a crisis. Let's say you're flung into a crisis, what do you do?

248
00:17:38,325 --> 00:17:45,887
So the first thing is to try to understand the issues thoroughly. When you first become

249
00:17:45,927 --> 00:17:51,208
aware of that people, everybody's upset and the forums are on fire, you won't know precisely

250
00:17:51,288 --> 00:17:56,270
why that is. And you'll get bits and pieces of the story, but you need to make sure that

251
00:17:56,330 --> 00:17:59,190
you have asked enough questions until you understand the whole story.

252
00:18:00,493 --> 00:18:08,358
For instance, problem is the game is down. Okay, that's a problem. But sometimes it's

253
00:18:08,378 --> 00:18:13,541
really that the game is down and we're missing an event. Sometimes it's that the game is

254
00:18:13,581 --> 00:18:17,423
down and we wrote to support and told them about it and they said, oh, no, the game is

255
00:18:17,463 --> 00:18:18,064
just fine.

256
00:18:19,392 --> 00:18:23,637
So in the second two scenarios, you have an additional problem that you need to think

257
00:18:23,697 --> 00:18:27,301
about before this whole thing is going to be wrapped up.

258
00:18:27,381 --> 00:18:32,927
Just getting the game back online won't really solve it if people are still going to be mad

259
00:18:32,987 --> 00:18:35,970
about the time they missed in the event or mad that support blew them off.

260
00:18:36,931 --> 00:18:39,173
So make sure you understand the whole problem.

261
00:18:42,229 --> 00:18:44,851
Remember to apologize or express regret.

262
00:18:45,711 --> 00:18:51,316
This is something that's really easy to forget because of course we're all thinking, you

263
00:18:51,356 --> 00:18:53,017
know that I didn't do this on purpose.

264
00:18:54,358 --> 00:18:58,722
But players won't necessarily take that for granted.

265
00:18:58,922 --> 00:19:03,946
They're human and human beings want to have their distress acknowledged by other humans.

266
00:19:07,034 --> 00:19:10,135
And expressing regret or empathy is a way that we do that for each other.

267
00:19:11,295 --> 00:19:15,397
So for instance, if somebody's grandmother dies, you say, I'm really sorry to hear that.

268
00:19:15,857 --> 00:19:19,858
Now you're not saying, you're right, I killed your grandmother and I'm super sorry for doing

269
00:19:19,898 --> 00:19:20,098
that.

270
00:19:20,418 --> 00:19:24,060
No, you're saying I'm sorry that you're experiencing regret and loss and pain.

271
00:19:25,499 --> 00:19:30,620
So the same goes for communities. These sorts of statements that are up here will let people

272
00:19:30,680 --> 00:19:36,461
know that they have been heard and that you sympathize. And, of course, if you had a part

273
00:19:36,641 --> 00:19:41,042
in creating the problem or making it worse, you should take it a step farther and actually

274
00:19:41,082 --> 00:19:48,764
apologize for that as well. So this is another one of those things that

275
00:19:48,824 --> 00:19:53,525
seems really obvious and yet in the moment it's going to be easy to forget. Explain

276
00:19:53,565 --> 00:19:54,665
your next steps.

277
00:19:56,305 --> 00:20:00,429
Remember, you're in a situation where people are not feeling very trusting of you.

278
00:20:00,549 --> 00:20:02,991
They have concerns about whether or not you're going to do a good job.

279
00:20:03,551 --> 00:20:09,537
So the best way to start getting them back on track is, or getting trust rebuilt, I should

280
00:20:09,577 --> 00:20:12,720
say, is to tell them what you're going to do.

281
00:20:13,600 --> 00:20:16,963
Otherwise they're going to be like, oh, so she's going to go down and kick the servers,

282
00:20:17,024 --> 00:20:17,224
right?

283
00:20:18,098 --> 00:20:23,900
No, but I can call the people who can, you know, reboot the whatever it is.

284
00:20:24,300 --> 00:20:25,740
See, that's my tech knowledge right there.

285
00:20:30,321 --> 00:20:33,142
So make sure that their expectations are ones that you can actually meet.

286
00:20:34,422 --> 00:20:37,862
And then, this is also important, do it.

287
00:20:38,383 --> 00:20:41,243
Don't just say it and then be like, yeah, well, I'll get to it.

288
00:20:41,963 --> 00:20:42,283
Do it.

289
00:20:43,364 --> 00:20:45,544
And report back.

290
00:20:47,047 --> 00:20:52,869
Don't just because you said you'll do something and you know that you're a person of integrity,

291
00:20:53,149 --> 00:20:58,690
so of course you've done it, but the players are in a situation where they're not feeling

292
00:20:58,710 --> 00:20:59,291
very trusting.

293
00:20:59,931 --> 00:21:03,332
And so they're not going to go like, oh, well, she said she would do it, so I guess she did.

294
00:21:04,174 --> 00:21:06,235
Now, they're going to be like, well, who knows?

295
00:21:06,576 --> 00:21:09,058
So just go back, hey, I did that thing.

296
00:21:09,278 --> 00:21:09,839
Is it better?

297
00:21:09,979 --> 00:21:11,100
How's everybody feeling?

298
00:21:12,261 --> 00:21:18,706
And so you want to keep iterating that until people are reporting that they feel better,

299
00:21:18,726 --> 00:21:20,688
that they think the situation is improved.

300
00:21:22,710 --> 00:21:23,951
Not everybody's going to be happy.

301
00:21:25,472 --> 00:21:30,597
But if most people feel like you have done everything you can, then that's what you can do.

302
00:21:35,560 --> 00:21:39,502
A last note that I had originally left out of my outline, but my manager pointed out

303
00:21:39,542 --> 00:21:42,503
to me that it was important, because I took it for granted.

304
00:21:42,603 --> 00:21:43,883
See this is how crises go.

305
00:21:43,943 --> 00:21:46,004
These things are so obvious that we take them for granted.

306
00:21:46,904 --> 00:21:47,764
Do better next time.

307
00:21:50,245 --> 00:21:54,807
The first time you make a mistake or your team makes a mistake, your community will

308
00:21:55,267 --> 00:21:57,348
forgive you, assuming you, you know, make it right.

309
00:21:58,684 --> 00:22:00,966
Long about the fifth time you make the same mistake.

310
00:22:01,887 --> 00:22:05,169
It won't matter what you say or what kind of compensation you give.

311
00:22:05,189 --> 00:22:06,530
They're not going to trust you again.

312
00:22:08,232 --> 00:22:11,574
So I had that slide about the postmortem.

313
00:22:11,634 --> 00:22:15,677
Be sure to have one of those and have it be an actual meeting, not just a couple of conversations

314
00:22:15,718 --> 00:22:16,278
in the hallway.

315
00:22:16,979 --> 00:22:17,519
Take notes.

316
00:22:18,239 --> 00:22:23,884
Come up with a plan for how you're going to change your flow in the future so that these

317
00:22:23,924 --> 00:22:24,765
things don't happen again.

318
00:22:29,305 --> 00:22:33,228
So this is not the most beautiful slide in my presentation.

319
00:22:33,629 --> 00:22:36,011
But anyway, an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure.

320
00:22:36,051 --> 00:22:37,312
It's better than a pound of cure.

321
00:22:38,092 --> 00:22:40,855
So I'm gonna talk a little bit now about some pitfalls.

322
00:22:42,136 --> 00:22:43,837
I've talked about how to handle the crises

323
00:22:43,877 --> 00:22:44,898
that you find yourself in,

324
00:22:45,459 --> 00:22:48,862
but it's even better if you can steer your community

325
00:22:48,922 --> 00:22:51,444
between the pitfalls so that you don't end up

326
00:22:51,524 --> 00:22:53,286
in a hole in the first place, right?

327
00:22:54,707 --> 00:22:56,428
And these two are based in...

328
00:22:57,604 --> 00:22:59,425
Some people that I've seen end up in holes.

