00:27:40,264 --> 00:27:41,985
And he's still playing an assortment of games.

399
00:27:42,485 --> 00:27:45,907
He occasionally has a kind of a feisty forum post, but nothing like it was before.

400
00:27:46,993 --> 00:27:53,456
So it is possible to sort of win people over and have them become more productive members

401
00:27:53,516 --> 00:27:55,777
of your community instead of destructive ones.

402
00:27:58,558 --> 00:28:04,240
And the thing that I want to highlight, too, is that handling negative feedback calmly

403
00:28:04,600 --> 00:28:07,321
and without defensiveness makes everyone respect you more.

404
00:28:08,994 --> 00:28:13,857
If someone is trying to upset you, the solution is to get as unupset as you can.

405
00:28:14,838 --> 00:28:17,260
It makes you in charge of the situation and not them.

406
00:28:18,781 --> 00:28:23,364
Beyond that, if someone has negative feedback, consider what they have to say.

407
00:28:24,744 --> 00:28:27,306
Even if they're being a jerk, they might have some good insights.

408
00:28:28,127 --> 00:28:32,730
One of the most important lessons I ever learned about moderation was back when I was a volunteer

409
00:28:32,750 --> 00:28:33,430
chat moderator.

410
00:28:34,011 --> 00:28:35,351
We had a truly awful user.

411
00:28:37,049 --> 00:28:39,297
And he made a point to me one day and I went, oh.

412
00:28:40,682 --> 00:28:41,605
And what he said.

413
00:28:42,507 --> 00:28:48,231
It basically formed the entire basis of a bunch of the stuff I've talked to you about

414
00:28:48,932 --> 00:28:51,834
and was this huge gift to my future professional career.

415
00:28:52,414 --> 00:28:58,259
But it came in this poop and insult covered wrapper that if I had thrown it away, I would

416
00:28:58,299 --> 00:29:04,523
never have realized that there was really a kernel of really good information there.

417
00:29:04,923 --> 00:29:05,964
So I'm glad I didn't do that.

418
00:29:06,024 --> 00:29:07,305
And I encourage you to do the same.

419
00:29:08,366 --> 00:29:10,708
Sometimes even jerks have good points.

420
00:29:12,378 --> 00:29:19,527
And so and similarly, like, of course you're going to feel defensive, right?

421
00:29:19,607 --> 00:29:21,990
Like I know that we can't

422
00:29:23,110 --> 00:29:27,292
hear people say terrible things about us and not feel a smidgen of defensiveness.

423
00:29:27,812 --> 00:29:28,833
Well, okay, most of us can't.

424
00:29:29,473 --> 00:29:31,954
But you don't have to let on that you're feeling that way, right?

425
00:29:32,334 --> 00:29:37,136
So just sort of move that emotion into a separate place and be like, oh, okay, I'm sorry to

426
00:29:37,156 --> 00:29:38,097
hear you feel that way.

427
00:29:38,137 --> 00:29:39,077
Let's talk about that.

428
00:29:39,697 --> 00:29:43,339
And suddenly the situation is going to diffuse.

429
00:29:45,960 --> 00:29:46,140
Now

430
00:29:47,620 --> 00:29:52,022
So this is the moderate path, right, which means that it's possible to err on one side

431
00:29:52,122 --> 00:29:54,123
and it's possible to err on the other side as well.

432
00:29:55,144 --> 00:30:01,287
So you want to listen to players, but it's also possible to listen too much or to be

433
00:30:01,367 --> 00:30:02,647
too responsive when you listen.

434
00:30:03,187 --> 00:30:04,728
It's less common, but it still happens.

435
00:30:06,265 --> 00:30:08,727
In my experience, it's usually when a game dev is just starting out.

436
00:30:09,108 --> 00:30:10,469
Maybe their team is very small.

437
00:30:11,910 --> 00:30:13,872
So every time they make a change or a tweak,

438
00:30:14,193 --> 00:30:15,634
then they go and they listen in the forums.

439
00:30:15,674 --> 00:30:16,635
What do you guys think?

440
00:30:16,735 --> 00:30:17,376
Do you love it?

441
00:30:17,396 --> 00:30:20,179
Oh, you didn't love it?

442
00:30:20,199 --> 00:30:22,020
Oh, what could I do that would make you love it?

443
00:30:23,722 --> 00:30:26,665
And so sometimes then the developers will go and make...

444
00:30:27,549 --> 00:30:30,191
Big changes to the game based on the feedback they got.

445
00:30:30,731 --> 00:30:32,652
Which seems amazing, right?

446
00:30:32,692 --> 00:30:39,898
It seems egalitarian and it seems very collaborative and all these really things that feel really

447
00:30:39,958 --> 00:30:40,218
good.

448
00:30:41,619 --> 00:30:44,121
But there is a downside to this.

449
00:30:46,282 --> 00:30:53,848
Which is that sooner or later, players are going to develop a sense of entitlement.

450
00:30:54,068 --> 00:30:56,310
They're going to feel entitled to that level of attention.

451
00:30:57,364 --> 00:31:00,726
So, then the question becomes what happens when the developer is a success?

452
00:31:01,747 --> 00:31:06,470
And when they inevitably, as they must do, start to make a new game and start shifting

453
00:31:06,490 --> 00:31:07,691
their attention somewhere else?

454
00:31:07,811 --> 00:31:13,115
What happens, in my experience, is that the players can get really toxic and they can

455
00:31:13,155 --> 00:31:16,557
get really angry and embittered by the loss of attention.

456
00:31:18,939 --> 00:31:20,741
This next slide is one I forgot to remove.

